  '77777777-7777-7777-7777-700000000001',
  'Building a Production-Ready On-Demand Mobility App with React Native and Firebase',
  'building-on-demand-mobility-app-react-native-firebase',
  '66666666-6666-6666-6666-600000000004',
  'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1449965408869-eaa3f722e40d?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop',
  'Rafael Pilartes',
  '/t-avt-1.png',
  'A deep dive into the real architecture decisions, challenges, and solutions behind building Kandengue Atrevido — an Uber-style mobility platform built for Angola using React Native, Firebase, and a Fastify API.',
  $$ {"raw": "", "text": "## From Idea to Production: The Real Story of Kandengue Atrevido\n\nBuilding an on-demand mobility platform is one of the most technically demanding challenges in mobile development. It requires real-time location tracking, bidirectional state synchronization, payment integrations, and two separate apps (passenger and driver) that must communicate seamlessly.\n\nThis is the story of how I built **Kandengue Atrevido** — a ride-hailing ecosystem for the Angolan market.\n\n### The Architecture Decision\n\nFrom day one, I chose **Clean Architecture** as the foundation:\n\n```\nView → ViewModel → Use Case → Repository → Service\n```\n\nThis separation meant that swapping Firebase for a REST API in the future would only affect the Service layer — the rest of the codebase remains untouched.\n\n### Tech Stack\n\n- **React Native 0.81.5** (Bare workflow) + **Expo 54**\n- **Firebase** (Firestore, Auth, Cloud Functions)\n- **Zustand** for global state management\n- **NativeWind** for styling\n- **TanStack Query** for server state\n- **Fastify + TypeScript** for the backend API\n\n### The Real-Time Location Challenge\n\nThe biggest technical challenge was broadcasting driver location to passengers in real time without destroying battery life or overwhelming Firestore with writes.\n\nThe solution: throttle location updates to every **3 seconds** on the driver side, and use Firestore `onSnapshot` listeners on the passenger side with geohash-based filtering to only listen to drivers within a relevant radius.\n\n```typescript\n// Driver app — throttled location broadcast\nconst broadcastLocation = useCallback(\n  throttle(async (coords: Coords) => {\n    await driverRepository.updateLocation({\n      driverId: user.id,\n      lat: coords.latitude,\n      lng: coords.longitude,\n      geohash: encodeGeohash(coords.latitude, coords.longitude, 6),\n    });\n  }, 3000),\n  [user.id]\n);\n```\n\n### Payment Integration: Unitel Money\n\nIntegrating with **Unitel Money** (Angola's leading mobile payment provider) was the most complex part of the backend. The API requires RSA-encrypted credentials and a specific XML-based SOAP-like request format.\n\nI built a dedicated Fastify service with a reconciliation job that runs every 2 minutes to catch any failed or pending top-up transactions — ensuring no user ever loses money due to a network timeout.\n\n### Lessons Learned\n\n1. **Always throttle location writes** — Firestore costs scale with writes, not reads.\n2. **Separate your apps early** — Passenger and driver apps share zero UI but share domain logic via a common package.\n3. **Build reconciliation from day one** — Payment flows will fail. Design for it.\n4. **Test on real African networks** — 3G with 400ms latency changes everything about your UX assumptions.\n\nKandengue Atrevido is now live in production. The journey from whiteboard to the Play Store taught me more about real-world engineering than any course ever could."} $$::jsonb,
  '2025-02-10'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

-- POST 2
  '77777777-7777-7777-7777-700000000002',
  'Clean Architecture in React Native: A Practical Guide with Real Code',
  'clean-architecture-react-native-practical-guide',
  '66666666-6666-6666-6666-600000000005',
  'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1627398225058-eb56a6eb3915?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop',
  'Rafael Pilartes',
  '/t-avt-1.png',
  'Stop putting everything in your screens. Here is how I structure every React Native project using Clean Architecture — with real folder structures, real code, and real reasons why it matters at scale.',
  $$ {"raw": "", "text": "## Why Clean Architecture in Mobile?\n\nMost React Native tutorials show you how to build a feature. Very few show you how to build a **system**. The difference becomes painfully obvious when your app grows beyond 10 screens and your `useEffect` hooks start looking like spaghetti.\n\nClean Architecture solves this by enforcing a strict dependency rule: **outer layers depend on inner layers, never the reverse.**\n\n### The 5-Layer Structure I Use\n\n```\nsrc/\n├── presentation/     # Screens, Components, ViewModels\n├── domain/           # Use Cases, Entities, Repository Interfaces\n├── data/             # Repository Implementations, Services\n├── infrastructure/   # Firebase, API clients, Storage\n└── shared/           # Utils, constants, types\n```\n\n### Layer 1: The Entity\n\nEntities are pure business objects. No Firebase, no Axios, no React — just data and logic.\n\n```typescript\n// domain/entities/Trip.ts\nexport class Trip {\n  constructor(\n    public readonly id: string,\n    public readonly passengerId: string,\n    public readonly driverId: string | null,\n    public readonly status: TripStatus,\n    public readonly origin: GeoPoint,\n    public readonly destination: GeoPoint,\n    public readonly createdAt: Date,\n  ) {}\n\n  isActive(): boolean {\n    return [TripStatus.SEARCHING, TripStatus.ACCEPTED, TripStatus.IN_PROGRESS].includes(this.status);\n  }\n\n  canBeCancelledBy(userId: string): boolean {\n    return this.passengerId === userId && this.status === TripStatus.SEARCHING;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Layer 2: The Repository Interface\n\nThe domain defines **what** it needs. It does not care **how** it gets it.\n\n```typescript\n// domain/repositories/ITripRepository.ts\nexport interface ITripRepository {\n  create(trip: CreateTripDTO): Promise<Trip>;\n  findById(id: string): Promise<Trip | null>;\n  listenToActiveTrip(passengerId: string, callback: (trip: Trip | null) => void): Unsubscribe;\n  updateStatus(id: string, status: TripStatus): Promise<void>;\n}\n```\n\n### Layer 3: The Use Case\n\nUse cases orchestrate business logic. One use case = one action.\n\n```typescript\n// domain/usecases/RequestTripUseCase.ts\nexport class RequestTripUseCase {\n  constructor(private tripRepository: ITripRepository) {}\n\n  async execute(input: RequestTripInput): Promise<Trip> {\n    const trip = new Trip(\n      generateId(),\n      input.passengerId,\n      null,\n      TripStatus.SEARCHING,\n      input.origin,\n      input.destination,\n      new Date(),\n    );\n    return this.tripRepository.create(trip);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Layer 4: The ViewModel\n\nViewModels connect use cases to the UI. They hold state and expose actions.\n\n```typescript\n// presentation/viewmodels/useRequestTripViewModel.ts\nexport function useRequestTripViewModel() {\n  const [state, setState] = useState<RequestTripState>({ status: 'idle' });\n  const requestTrip = useRequestTripUseCase(); // injected via context\n\n  const handleRequest = async (input: RequestTripInput) => {\n    setState({ status: 'loading' });\n    try {\n      const trip = await requestTrip.execute(input);\n      setState({ status: 'success', trip });\n    } catch (error) {\n      setState({ status: 'error', message: error.message });\n    }\n  };\n\n  return { state, handleRequest };\n}\n```\n\n### The Result\n\nWith this structure, I can:\n- **Unit test** every use case without mounting a single component\n- **Swap Firebase** for a REST API by only changing the data layer\n- **Onboard new developers** who immediately understand where everything lives\n\nThis is the architecture I used in Kandengue Atrevido, and it scaled from MVP to production without a single major refactor."} $$::jsonb,
  '2025-01-20'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

