  '77777777-7777-7777-7777-700000000003',
  'Integrating Mobile Payments in Africa: A Developer''s Guide to Unitel Money API',
  'integrating-unitel-money-api-angola-developer-guide',
  '66666666-6666-6666-6666-600000000001',
  'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1556742049-0cfed4f6a45d?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop',
  'Rafael Pilartes',
  '/t-avt-1.png',
  'A practical, honest guide to integrating Unitel Money — Angola''s leading mobile payment provider — into a Node.js/Fastify backend. Including RSA encryption, error handling, and building a reconciliation job for failed transactions.',
  $$ {"raw": "", "text": "## The Reality of African Payment APIs\n\nIntegrating payments in Africa is a different beast from Stripe or PayPal. The documentation is sparse, the error messages are cryptic, and the APIs often use legacy protocols. But it is absolutely worth it — mobile money is how millions of Angolans transact every day.\n\nThis guide covers everything I learned integrating **Unitel Money** into the Kandengue Atrevido backend.\n\n### Prerequisites\n\n- A registered developer account on the [Unitel API Gateway](https://apigateway.unitel.co.ao:9443/devportal/)\n- Your assigned **ShortCode** and **Identifier**\n- An RSA key pair for credential encryption\n\n### Step 1: Generating the Security Credential\n\nUnitel requires your PIN to be RSA-encrypted using their public certificate before every request. I wrote a dedicated script for this:\n\n```typescript\n// scripts/generate-credential.ts\nimport crypto from 'crypto';\nimport fs from 'fs';\n\nexport function generateSecurityCredential(pin: string, certPath: string): string {\n  const cert = fs.readFileSync(certPath);\n  const encrypted = crypto.publicEncrypt(\n    {\n      key: cert,\n      padding: crypto.constants.RSA_PKCS1_PADDING,\n    },\n    Buffer.from(pin)\n  );\n  return encrypted.toString('base64');\n}\n```\n\n### Step 2: The Top-Up Flow\n\nThe wallet top-up flow has 3 stages:\n1. **Initiate** — Send the top-up request to Unitel\n2. **Poll** — Check the transaction status (Unitel is async)\n3. **Confirm** — Update your database when confirmed\n\n```typescript\n// services/UnitelMoneyService.ts\nexport class UnitelMoneyService {\n  async initiateTopUp(input: TopUpInput): Promise<string> {\n    const response = await this.client.post('/topup/initiate', {\n      shortCode: process.env.UNITEL_SHORT_CODE,\n      identifier: process.env.UNITEL_IDENTIFIER,\n      msisdn: input.phoneNumber,\n      amount: input.amount,\n      securityCredential: this.securityCredential,\n      transactionRef: input.transactionRef,\n    });\n    return response.data.transactionId;\n  }\n\n  async checkStatus(transactionId: string): Promise<TransactionStatus> {\n    const response = await this.client.get(`/topup/status/${transactionId}`);\n    return response.data.status as TransactionStatus;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Step 3: The Reconciliation Job\n\nNetwork failures happen. A user might lose connectivity right after initiating a payment. Without reconciliation, that transaction stays pending forever.\n\nI built a job that runs every **2 minutes** to check all pending transactions:\n\n```typescript\n// jobs/reconcile-pending-topups.job.ts\nexport async function reconcilePendingTopUps() {\n  const pending = await topUpRepository.findByStatus('PENDING');\n  \n  for (const topUp of pending) {\n    const status = await unitelService.checkStatus(topUp.transactionId);\n    \n    if (status === 'SUCCESS') {\n      await topUpRepository.updateStatus(topUp.id, 'SUCCESS');\n      await walletRepository.credit(topUp.userId, topUp.amount);\n      await notificationService.send(topUp.userId, 'top_up_success', topUp.amount);\n    } else if (status === 'FAILED') {\n      await topUpRepository.updateStatus(topUp.id, 'FAILED');\n      await notificationService.send(topUp.userId, 'top_up_failed');\n    }\n    // If still PENDING, leave it for the next run\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Key Lessons\n\n1. **Never trust a single API response** — always reconcile async payments\n2. **Log everything** — Pino structured logs saved me hours of debugging\n3. **Idempotency keys** — Generate a unique `transactionRef` per attempt to prevent double charges\n4. **Test with real SIMs** — The sandbox environment does not behave like production\n\nPayment integration is where your app earns real trust. Get it right."} $$::jsonb,
  '2025-03-05'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

