  '77777777-7777-7777-7777-700000000004',
  'Fastify vs Express in 2025: Why I Switched and Never Looked Back',
  'fastify-vs-express-2025-why-i-switched',
  '66666666-6666-6666-6666-600000000003',
  'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1558494949-ef010cbdcc31?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop',
  'Rafael Pilartes',
  '/t-avt-1.png',
  'After years of building APIs with Express, I switched to Fastify for the Kandengue Atrevido backend. Here is an honest comparison — performance numbers, DX differences, and the one feature that sealed the deal for me.',
  $$ {"raw": "", "text": "## The Switch I Did Not Expect to Make\n\nI built my first Node.js API with Express in 2019. It was simple, familiar, and had a massive ecosystem. For years, I never questioned it.\n\nThen I started building the Kandengue Atrevido backend and decided to try **Fastify**. Six months later, I cannot imagine going back.\n\n### Performance: The Numbers\n\nFastify is consistently **2-3x faster** than Express in benchmarks. On a real production server handling ride requests:\n\n| Metric | Express | Fastify |\n|:---|:---|:---|\n| Requests/sec | ~14,000 | ~30,000 |\n| Latency (p99) | ~12ms | ~5ms |\n| Memory usage | ~85MB | ~60MB |\n\nFor a mobility app where every millisecond affects the user experience of requesting a ride, this matters.\n\n### Schema Validation Out of the Box\n\nThis is the feature that sealed the deal. Fastify uses **JSON Schema** for request/response validation natively — no extra middleware needed.\n\n```typescript\n// With Fastify + TypeBox\nconst TopUpSchema = Type.Object({\n  phoneNumber: Type.String({ pattern: '^244[0-9]{9}$' }),\n  amount: Type.Number({ minimum: 100, maximum: 50000 }),\n});\n\nfastify.post('/wallet/topup', {\n  schema: { body: TopUpSchema },\n  handler: async (request, reply) => {\n    // request.body is fully typed AND validated\n    const { phoneNumber, amount } = request.body;\n    // ...\n  }\n});\n```\n\nWith Express, I needed Zod + a custom middleware + manual type assertions. With Fastify, the schema IS the type.\n\n### Plugin Architecture\n\nFastify's plugin system with `fastify-plugin` is genuinely elegant. Encapsulation is built in — plugins registered inside a scope do not leak to the parent.\n\n```typescript\n// Registering the payment plugin\nfastify.register(async (instance) => {\n  instance.decorate('unitelService', new UnitelMoneyService());\n  instance.register(topUpRoutes);\n}, { prefix: '/api/v1' });\n```\n\n### When to Still Use Express\n\n- You need a specific middleware that only exists for Express\n- Your team is deeply familiar with Express and the project is short-term\n- You are building a simple proxy or BFF with minimal logic\n\n### My Verdict\n\nFor any new Node.js API in 2025, **start with Fastify**. The performance gains are real, the TypeScript integration is first-class, and the schema validation alone will save you hundreds of lines of boilerplate."} $$::jsonb,
  '2025-01-08'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

