  '77777777-7777-7777-7777-700000000005',
  'Zustand vs Redux in 2025: The State Management Decision That Changed My Workflow',
  'zustand-vs-redux-2025-state-management',
  '66666666-6666-6666-6666-600000000002',
  'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1633356122544-f134324a6cee?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop',
  'Rafael Pilartes',
  '/t-avt-1.png',
  'I used Redux for 3 years. Then I tried Zustand on a real production app and wrote 80% less boilerplate. Here is a practical comparison with real code from the Kandengue Atrevido passenger app.',
  $$ {"raw": "", "text": "## The Boilerplate Problem\n\nRedux is powerful. Redux is also verbose. For every feature, you write: an action type, an action creator, a reducer case, a selector, and a thunk. That is 5 files for one feature.\n\n**Zustand** collapses all of that into one store file.\n\n### The Same Feature in Both\n\n**Redux (simplified):**\n```typescript\n// actions/tripActions.ts\nexport const SET_ACTIVE_TRIP = 'SET_ACTIVE_TRIP';\nexport const setActiveTrip = (trip: Trip) => ({ type: SET_ACTIVE_TRIP, payload: trip });\n\n// reducers/tripReducer.ts\nconst initialState = { activeTrip: null, loading: false };\nexport function tripReducer(state = initialState, action) {\n  switch (action.type) {\n    case SET_ACTIVE_TRIP: return { ...state, activeTrip: action.payload };\n    default: return state;\n  }\n}\n\n// selectors/tripSelectors.ts\nexport const selectActiveTrip = (state: RootState) => state.trip.activeTrip;\n```\n\n**Zustand:**\n```typescript\n// stores/useTripStore.ts\ninterface TripStore {\n  activeTrip: Trip | null;\n  setActiveTrip: (trip: Trip | null) => void;\n}\n\nexport const useTripStore = create<TripStore>((set) => ({\n  activeTrip: null,\n  setActiveTrip: (trip) => set({ activeTrip: trip }),\n}));\n```\n\nSame result. One file. Zero boilerplate.\n\n### Zustand with Persistence\n\nOne of the most common needs in a mobile app is persisting state across app restarts. With Zustand and `zustand/middleware`:\n\n```typescript\nimport { persist, createJSONStorage } from 'zustand/middleware';\nimport AsyncStorage from '@react-native-async-storage/async-storage';\n\nexport const useAuthStore = create(\n  persist<AuthStore>(\n    (set) => ({\n      user: null,\n      token: null,\n      setUser: (user) => set({ user }),\n      logout: () => set({ user: null, token: null }),\n    }),\n    {\n      name: 'auth-storage',\n      storage: createJSONStorage(() => AsyncStorage),\n    }\n  )\n);\n```\n\n### When Redux Still Makes Sense\n\n- Very large teams where strict patterns prevent chaos\n- Apps with extremely complex state interactions and time-travel debugging needs\n- Legacy codebases already on Redux\n\n### My Recommendation\n\nFor any new React Native project in 2025: **start with Zustand**. If you hit its limits (you probably won't), migrate to Redux Toolkit. The developer experience difference is night and day."} $$::jsonb,
  '2024-11-15'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

