  '77777777-7777-7777-7777-700000000007',
  'TypeScript Strict Mode: The 5 Patterns That Will Save Your Production App',
  'typescript-strict-mode-5-patterns-production',
  '66666666-6666-6666-6666-600000000002',
  'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516116216624-53e697fedbea?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop',
  'Rafael Pilartes',
  '/t-avt-1.png',
  'Enabling strict mode in TypeScript is easy. Using it correctly is hard. Here are 5 real patterns I use across every project to write TypeScript that actually prevents bugs — not just satisfies the compiler.',
  $$ {"raw": "", "text": "## Strict Mode Is Not Enough\n\nMost developers enable `strict: true` in their `tsconfig.json` and call it a day. But TypeScript strict mode is a floor, not a ceiling. Here are the patterns that actually make a difference in production.\n\n### Pattern 1: Branded Types for IDs\n\nUsing `string` for every ID is a silent bug factory. You can accidentally pass a `userId` where a `tripId` is expected and TypeScript will not complain.\n\n```typescript\n// Without branded types — TypeScript allows this bug\nfunction getTrip(tripId: string) { /* ... */ }\nconst userId = 'user_123';\ngetTrip(userId); // No error! But this is wrong.\n\n// With branded types — TypeScript catches it\ntype TripId = string & { readonly __brand: 'TripId' };\ntype UserId = string & { readonly __brand: 'UserId' };\n\nfunction getTrip(tripId: TripId) { /* ... */ }\nconst userId = 'user_123' as UserId;\ngetTrip(userId); // Error: Argument of type 'UserId' is not assignable to 'TripId'\n```\n\n### Pattern 2: Exhaustive Switch with `never`\n\nWhen you add a new status to an enum, you want TypeScript to force you to handle it everywhere.\n\n```typescript\ntype TripStatus = 'SEARCHING' | 'ACCEPTED' | 'IN_PROGRESS' | 'COMPLETED' | 'CANCELLED';\n\nfunction getTripStatusLabel(status: TripStatus): string {\n  switch (status) {\n    case 'SEARCHING': return 'Looking for a driver...';\n    case 'ACCEPTED': return 'Driver is on the way';\n    case 'IN_PROGRESS': return 'Trip in progress';\n    case 'COMPLETED': return 'Trip completed';\n    case 'CANCELLED': return 'Trip cancelled';\n    default:\n      const _exhaustive: never = status; // Error if a case is missing\n      throw new Error(`Unhandled status: ${_exhaustive}`);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 3: `satisfies` for Config Objects\n\nThe `satisfies` operator (TS 4.9+) validates a value against a type without widening it.\n\n```typescript\ntype Config = Record<string, { url: string; timeout: number }>;\n\nconst apiConfig = {\n  unitel: { url: 'https://apigateway.unitel.co.ao', timeout: 5000 },\n  firebase: { url: 'https://firestore.googleapis.com', timeout: 3000 },\n} satisfies Config;\n\n// apiConfig.unitel.url is still typed as string literal, not just string\n```\n\n### Pattern 4: Discriminated Unions for API Responses\n\nStop using `data | null` and `error | null` together. Use discriminated unions.\n\n```typescript\ntype ApiResult<T> =\n  | { success: true; data: T }\n  | { success: false; error: string; code: number };\n\nasync function fetchTrip(id: TripId): Promise<ApiResult<Trip>> {\n  try {\n    const trip = await tripRepository.findById(id);\n    return { success: true, data: trip };\n  } catch (e) {\n    return { success: false, error: e.message, code: 500 };\n  }\n}\n\n// Usage — TypeScript narrows correctly\nconst result = await fetchTrip(tripId);\nif (result.success) {\n  console.log(result.data.status); // Trip is available here\n} else {\n  console.error(result.error); // Error is available here\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 5: `Readonly` for Domain Entities\n\nEntities should be immutable after creation. Use `Readonly<T>` or `as const` to enforce this.\n\n```typescript\nfunction createTrip(input: CreateTripInput): Readonly<Trip> {\n  return Object.freeze({\n    id: generateId() as TripId,\n    passengerId: input.passengerId,\n    status: 'SEARCHING' as TripStatus,\n    createdAt: new Date(),\n  });\n}\n```\n\nThese 5 patterns have caught real bugs in production before they shipped. TypeScript is only as powerful as the patterns you apply."} $$::jsonb,
  '2024-10-03'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

-- POST 8
  '77777777-7777-7777-7777-700000000008',
  'Designing for Africa: UI/UX Principles That Actually Work in Low-Bandwidth Environments',
  'ui-ux-design-africa-low-bandwidth-principles',
  '66666666-6666-6666-6666-600000000003',
  'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551650975-87deedd944c3?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop',
  'Rafael Pilartes',
  '/t-avt-1.png',
  'Building apps for African markets requires rethinking assumptions about connectivity, device specs, and user behavior. Here are the design and engineering principles I apply when building for Angola and beyond.',
  $$ {"raw": "", "text": "## The Assumptions That Will Break Your App\n\nMost UI/UX tutorials assume:\n- A fast, stable internet connection\n- A flagship smartphone with 6GB RAM\n- A user who reads English fluently\n- Unlimited mobile data\n\nIn Angola, and across much of Africa, none of these assumptions hold. Here is how I design differently.\n\n### Principle 1: Offline-First, Always\n\nNetwork requests will fail. Design for it from the start, not as an afterthought.\n\nIn Kandengue Atrevido, every critical user action has an offline fallback:\n- **Trip history** is cached locally with AsyncStorage\n- **Driver location** degrades gracefully to last known position\n- **Payment status** is reconciled when connectivity returns\n\n```typescript\n// Optimistic UI with rollback\nconst requestTrip = async (input: RequestTripInput) => {\n  // Show success immediately\n  setTripStatus('SEARCHING');\n  \n  try {\n    await tripUseCase.execute(input);\n  } catch (error) {\n    // Roll back on failure\n    setTripStatus('IDLE');\n    showError('Connection failed. Please try again.');\n  }\n};\n```\n\n### Principle 2: Skeleton Screens Over Spinners\n\nA spinner tells the user \"something is happening.\" A skeleton screen tells them \"here is what you are about to see.\" The perceived wait time drops significantly.\n\nIn React Native with NativeWind:\n```tsx\nfunction TripCardSkeleton() {\n  return (\n    <View className=\"bg-gray-800 rounded-2xl p-4 animate-pulse\">\n      <View className=\"h-4 bg-gray-700 rounded w-3/4 mb-2\" />\n      <View className=\"h-4 bg-gray-700 rounded w-1/2\" />\n    </View>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Principle 3: Compress Everything\n\nImages are the biggest performance killer on slow networks. My rules:\n- **Profile photos:** Max 80x80px, WebP format, served from CDN\n- **App icons and thumbnails:** SVG where possible, PNG otherwise\n- **Never load full-resolution images** in list views\n\n### Principle 4: Large Touch Targets\n\nMany users in Angola use their phones with one hand, often while in motion. The minimum touch target size I use is **48x48dp** — larger than Apple's 44pt recommendation.\n\n### Principle 5: Respect Data Costs\n\nMobile data in Angola is expensive relative to income. Features that consume data should be opt-in:\n- Auto-play video: **off by default**\n- High-quality audio streaming: **only on WiFi by default**\n- Background sync: **user-controlled**\n\n### The Result\n\nApplying these principles to Kandengue Atrevido resulted in an app that works on 3G, runs smoothly on mid-range Android devices, and has a 4.2-star rating on the Play Store.\n\nDesigning for constraints makes you a better designer. The best apps work everywhere."} $$::jsonb,
  '2024-09-12'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

-- POST 9
  '77777777-7777-7777-7777-700000000009',
  'From Figma to Code: My Exact Design-to-Development Workflow in 2025',
  'figma-to-code-design-development-workflow-2025',
  '66666666-6666-6666-6666-600000000001',
  'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1561070791-2526d30994b5?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop',
  'Rafael Pilartes',
  '/t-avt-1.png',
  'As a developer who also designs, I have refined a workflow that eliminates the handoff problem entirely. Here is my exact process — from Figma components to production React Native code — with zero miscommunication.',
  $$ {"raw": "", "text": "## The Handoff Problem Does Not Exist If You Are Both\n\nThe traditional design-to-development handoff is a game of telephone. The designer creates a beautiful Figma file. The developer interprets it. Something is always lost.\n\nAs someone who both designs and develops, I have eliminated this problem entirely. Here is my workflow.\n\n### Step 1: Design Tokens First\n\nBefore designing a single screen, I define the design system in Figma:\n\n**Colors:**\n- `brand/primary` — the main action color\n- `brand/secondary` — supporting color\n- `surface/default`, `surface/elevated`, `surface/overlay`\n- `text/primary`, `text/secondary`, `text/disabled`\n- `status/success`, `status/error`, `status/warning`\n\n**Typography:**\n- `heading/xl`, `heading/lg`, `heading/md`\n- `body/lg`, `body/md`, `body/sm`\n- `label/lg`, `label/md`\n\n**Spacing:** 4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64\n\nThese tokens map directly to my `tailwind.config.ts`:\n\n```typescript\n// tailwind.config.ts\nexport default {\n  theme: {\n    extend: {\n      colors: {\n        brand: {\n          primary: '#D91C4A',\n          secondary: '#1C6ED9',\n        },\n        surface: {\n          default: '#0F0F0F',\n          elevated: '#1A1A1A',\n          overlay: '#252525',\n        },\n      },\n      fontFamily: {\n        heading: ['Inter-Bold', 'sans-serif'],\n        body: ['Inter-Regular', 'sans-serif'],\n      },\n    },\n  },\n};\n```\n\n### Step 2: Component-First Design\n\nI design components before screens. Every element in Figma is a component with variants:\n- `Button` — variants: primary, secondary, outline, ghost; states: default, hover, disabled, loading\n- `Input` — variants: default, error, success; states: empty, focused, filled\n- `Card` — variants: default, elevated, outlined\n\n### Step 3: Auto Layout = Flexbox\n\nEvery Figma frame uses Auto Layout. This maps directly to React Native's Flexbox model. If it works in Figma Auto Layout, it works in React Native.\n\n### Step 4: Component Implementation\n\n```tsx\n// components/ui/Button.tsx\ninterface ButtonProps {\n  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'outline' | 'ghost';\n  size?: 'sm' | 'md' | 'lg';\n  loading?: boolean;\n  disabled?: boolean;\n  onPress: () => void;\n  children: React.ReactNode;\n}\n\nexport function Button({ variant = 'primary', size = 'md', loading, disabled, onPress, children }: ButtonProps) {\n  return (\n    <Pressable\n      onPress={onPress}\n      disabled={disabled || loading}\n      className={cn(\n        'rounded-2xl items-center justify-center',\n        variant === 'primary' && 'bg-brand-primary',\n        variant === 'outline' && 'border border-brand-primary bg-transparent',\n        size === 'sm' && 'px-4 py-2',\n        size === 'md' && 'px-6 py-3',\n        size === 'lg' && 'px-8 py-4',\n        (disabled || loading) && 'opacity-50',\n      )}\n    >\n      {loading ? <ActivityIndicator color=\"white\" /> : children}\n    </Pressable>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### The Result\n\nWith this workflow, I go from a finalized Figma design to a working React Native screen in **2-4 hours** — not days. The design tokens ensure pixel-perfect consistency, and the component library means I am never rebuilding the same button twice."} $$::jsonb,
  '2024-07-05'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

-- POST 10
  '77777777-7777-7777-7777-700000000010',
  'Firebase Cloud Functions in Production: Patterns, Pitfalls, and Performance',
  'firebase-cloud-functions-production-patterns-pitfalls',
  '66666666-6666-6666-6666-600000000005',
  'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1544197150-b99a580bb7a8?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop',
  'Rafael Pilartes',
  '/t-avt-1.png',
  'Firebase Cloud Functions are powerful but easy to misuse. After running them in production for 2+ years across ToquePlay and Kandengue Atrevido, here are the patterns that work and the mistakes I will never make again.',
  $$ {"raw": "", "text": "## The Cold Start Problem Is Real\n\nFirebase Cloud Functions are serverless — they spin up on demand. The first invocation after a period of inactivity takes 1-3 seconds. For a ride-hailing app where a user expects instant confirmation, this is unacceptable.\n\nHere is how I handle it.\n\n### Pattern 1: Keep Critical Functions Warm\n\nFor functions on the critical path (trip creation, payment processing), I use a scheduled ping every 5 minutes:\n\n```typescript\n// functions/src/schedulers/keepWarm.ts\nexport const keepWarm = onSchedule('every 5 minutes', async () => {\n  // Ping critical HTTP functions to prevent cold starts\n  await Promise.all([\n    fetch(`${FUNCTIONS_BASE_URL}/createTrip/ping`),\n    fetch(`${FUNCTIONS_BASE_URL}/processPayment/ping`),\n  ]);\n});\n```\n\n### Pattern 2: Firestore Triggers for Side Effects\n\nNever call Cloud Functions directly from the client for side effects. Use Firestore triggers instead — they are more reliable and easier to debug.\n\n```typescript\n// functions/src/triggers/onTripStatusChange.ts\nexport const onTripStatusChange = onDocumentUpdated(\n  'trips/{tripId}',\n  async (event) => {\n    const before = event.data?.before.data() as Trip;\n    const after = event.data?.after.data() as Trip;\n\n    if (before.status === after.status) return; // No change\n\n    if (after.status === 'COMPLETED') {\n      await Promise.all([\n        calculateFare(after),\n        sendCompletionNotification(after.passengerId),\n        updateDriverStats(after.driverId),\n      ]);\n    }\n  }\n);\n```\n\n### Pattern 3: Idempotent Functions\n\nCloud Functions can be invoked multiple times for the same event (at-least-once delivery). Always make your functions idempotent.\n\n```typescript\nexport const processTopUp = onDocumentCreated(\n  'topups/{topupId}',\n  async (event) => {\n    const topup = event.data?.data() as TopUp;\n    \n    // Check if already processed\n    if (topup.processedAt) {\n      logger.info('TopUp already processed, skipping', { topupId: event.params.topupId });\n      return;\n    }\n\n    // Process and mark as done atomically\n    await db.runTransaction(async (tx) => {\n      tx.update(event.data!.ref, { processedAt: FieldValue.serverTimestamp() });\n      tx.update(walletRef(topup.userId), { balance: FieldValue.increment(topup.amount) });\n    });\n  }\n);\n```\n\n### Pattern 4: Structured Logging\n\nFirebase Functions logs go to Google Cloud Logging. Use structured logs to make them searchable.\n\n```typescript\nimport { logger } from 'firebase-functions';\n\nlogger.info('Trip created', {\n  tripId: trip.id,\n  passengerId: trip.passengerId,\n  origin: trip.origin,\n  timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),\n});\n```\n\n### The Mistakes I Made\n\n1. **Nested Firestore writes without transactions** — race conditions in concurrent updates\n2. **Unbounded queries in triggers** — a trigger that queries all trips will time out at scale\n3. **Secrets in environment variables without Secret Manager** — use `defineSecret()` instead\n4. **Not setting memory/timeout limits** — default 256MB and 60s is wrong for most functions\n\n```typescript\nexport const heavyProcessing = onRequest(\n  { memory: '1GiB', timeoutSeconds: 300 },\n  async (req, res) => { /* ... */ }\n);\n```\n\nCloud Functions are a superpower when used correctly. The patterns above are the result of 2 years of production experience."} $$::jsonb,
  '2024-06-18'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

-- POST 11
  '77777777-7777-7777-7777-700000000011',
  'How I Built My Portfolio with Next.js, Supabase, and a Full CMS — And What I Learned',
  'portfolio-nextjs-supabase-cms-lessons',
  '66666666-6666-6666-6666-600000000004',
  'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1467232004584-a241de8bcf5d?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop',
  'Rafael Pilartes',
  '/t-avt-1.png',
  'My portfolio is not just a static site — it is a full CMS-powered application built with Next.js 14, Supabase, and Clean Architecture. Here is why I over-engineered it on purpose, and what I learned from the process.',
  $$ {"raw": "", "text": "## Why Over-Engineer a Portfolio?\n\nMost developers build their portfolio with a static site generator and call it done. I built mine with a full CMS, admin panel, and Clean Architecture.\n\nWas it overkill? Technically, yes. Was it worth it? Absolutely.\n\nHere is why: **your portfolio is your most visible codebase**. Every recruiter, client, and collaborator who visits your site is also, implicitly, reviewing your engineering decisions. Make them count.\n\n### The Architecture\n\n```\nrafaelpilartes.com/\n├── app/                    # Next.js 14 App Router\n│   ├── (public)/           # Public-facing pages\n│   └── admin/              # Protected CMS admin panel\n├── core/\n│   ├── domain/             # Entities, Use Cases, Repository Interfaces\n│   ├── data/               # Supabase Repository Implementations\n│   └── infrastructure/     # Supabase client, storage\n└── components/\n    ├── ui/                 # Design system components\n    └── features/           # Feature-specific components\n```\n\n### Why Supabase Over Firebase?\n\nFor a content-heavy site with complex relational data (projects → technologies, blog posts → categories), a relational database is the right tool. Supabase gives me:\n\n- **PostgreSQL** — proper relational queries, joins, and full-text search\n- **Row Level Security** — admin routes protected at the database level\n- **Real-time subscriptions** — live preview in the admin panel\n- **Storage** — for project thumbnails and blog cover images\n\n```typescript\n// Fetching a project with its technologies in one query\nconst { data } = await supabase\n  .from('projects')\n  .select(`\n    *,\n    project_technologies (\n      technologies ( id, name, icon_svg )\n    )\n  `)\n  .eq('slug', slug)\n  .single();\n```\n\n### The Admin Panel\n\nThe admin panel is a protected Next.js route group with:\n- **Blog post editor** with rich text (Tiptap)\n- **Project manager** with drag-and-drop ordering\n- **Technology manager** with SVG icon upload\n- **Analytics dashboard** with Supabase Edge Functions\n\n### What I Learned\n\n1. **Next.js App Router is production-ready** — Server Components dramatically reduced client-side JavaScript\n2. **Supabase RLS is powerful but tricky** — spend time getting policies right before building features\n3. **Tiptap is the best rich text editor for React** — extensible, headless, and TypeScript-first\n4. **Over-engineering your portfolio is a feature** — it demonstrates real architectural thinking\n\nThe portfolio is live at [rafaelpilartes.com](https://rafaelpilartes.com). The code reflects the same standards I apply to every client project."} $$::jsonb,
  '2024-05-22'
)
ON CONFLICT (id) DO NOTHING;

